SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 1183
By Yager
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Connie Sue Long
Achenbach of Knoxville.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Connie Sue Long Achenbach; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Achenbach was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for her fellow citizens in
numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, born on December 5, 1943, in Kokomo, Indiana, to Robert Dean Long and
Emma Lucille Cook Long, Connie Achenbach was raised in a home deeply rooted in faith,
family, and service; at the age of eleven, she accepted Jesus Christ as her Lord and Savior and
surrendered her life to Him; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Achenbach attended school in Miami County, Indiana, before her
family moved to Michigan when she was twelve years old; in 1962, she graduated from high
school in Cass City, Michigan; and
WHEREAS, after graduating from high school, Connie Achenbach moved back to
Kokomo and began working at Delco Radio, where she met Robert "Bob" Earl Achenbach; and
WHEREAS, Bob Achenbach and Connie Sue Long married on June 5, 1965, and began
a life together filled with love for each other and for God; and
WHEREAS, in 1967, Mrs. Achenbach and her husband moved to Chicago, Illinois,
where they took night classes at Moody Bible Institute; in 1968, they moved to Grand Rapids,
Michigan, and attended Grand Rapids School of the Bible and Music, from which Mrs.
Achenbach graduated in 1971 as valedictorian of her class; and
SJR1183
018249
- 1 -

WHEREAS, after graduation, Connie and Bob Achenbach moved to Tennessee, where
they served the Lord at Cedine Ministries Bible Camp in Spring City and Trinity Baptist Church
in Harriman; and
WHEREAS, Connie Achenbach was deeply devoted to her family, and she always
endeavored to remain true to family values of the highest order; she loved taking care of her
family and her flowers; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Achenbach is survived by her sons, Jimmy (Tracey) Achenbach and
Jeff Achenbach; daughters, Debra (John) Keller and Angela Achenbach; brother, Ron (Jennifer)
Long; grandchildren, Hans Keller and Emma Keller; uncle, Mason (Jewell) Cook; and a host of
nieces, nephews, church family, and friends; and
WHEREAS, in addition to her parents and husband, she was preceded in death by her
brother, James Long; and
WHEREAS, Connie Sue Achenbach leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and
probity in public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all
her chosen endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should remember the
bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Connie Sue Long
Achenbach, reflecting fondly upon her impeccable character and her stalwart commitment to
living the examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mrs. Achenbach .
- 2 - 018249

BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
